Supplemental Table 5: Multivariable-adjusted hazard ratios (HRs) for any, total, and unique antimicrobial exposures in the marginal structural Cox regression model (MSM).

Characteristic Overall Survival Breast Cancer-Specific Survival
N Events Hazard Ratio (95% Confidence Interval) p-value N Events Hazard Ratio (95% Confidence Interval) p-value
Any antimicrobial exposure 171 1.46 (0.93 to 2.29) 0.10 124 1.39 (0.84 to 2.32) 0.20
Total antimicrobial exposures 205 1.05 (1.02 to 1.08) <0.001 142 1.05 (1.01 to 1.08) 0.005
Unique antimicrobial exposures 200 1.17 (1.12 to 1.23) <0.001 143 1.18 (1.13 to 1.24) <0.001
HRs reflect the risk of death for any antimicrobial use, defined as ever versus never receipt of antimicrobials, and the risk of death for each change in cumulative number of per-month prescriptions for total and unique exposures during observation. MSMs were adjusted for the following variables: age at diagnosis, race and ethnicity, socioeconomic status quintile, cancer stage, tumor grade, receipt of chemotherapy, receipt of radiotherapy, ever use of growth factor support, and surgery type
